1
00:00:01,902 --> 00:00:04,436
<i>When something begins,</i>

2
00:00:04,538 --> 00:00:08,640
<i>you generally have no
idea how it's going to end.</i>

3
00:00:08,742 --> 00:00:11,310
<i>The house you were going
to sell becomes your home.</i>

4
00:00:12,980 --> 00:00:16,681
<i>The roommates you were forced
to take in become your family.</i>

5
00:00:16,783 --> 00:00:19,802
<i>And the one-night stand
you were determined to forget</i>

6
00:00:19,904 --> 00:00:22,437
<i>becomes the love of your life.</i>

7
00:00:22,539 --> 00:00:25,574
Hey. How long have you been up?

8
00:00:25,676 --> 00:00:27,393
All night. I was
trying to figure out

9
00:00:27,495 --> 00:00:30,879
how to get the tumor
out of Izzie's brain.

10
00:00:30,981 --> 00:00:32,430
Then why are you smiling?

11
00:00:32,532 --> 00:00:34,099
'Cause I figured
out how to do it.

12
00:00:34,201 --> 00:00:36,668
Once Izzie's in the clear,
we go to the Bahamas,

13
00:00:36,771 --> 00:00:38,091
and have our
wedding on the beach.

14
00:00:38,172 --> 00:00:39,587
The One & Only Beach Club.

15
00:00:39,690 --> 00:00:41,924
You're gonna actually have
drinks during the ceremony.

16
00:00:42,026 --> 00:00:45,260
<i>♪ It just might
change your day ♪</i>

17
00:00:46,980 --> 00:00:48,363
Sure you're OK to
be up and around?

18
00:00:48,465 --> 00:00:51,566
Yes. I have good
days and bad days.

19
00:00:51,669 --> 00:00:55,336
I don't want to spend our entire
honeymoon in a hospital bed.

20
00:00:55,438 --> 00:00:58,907
- This is not our honeymoon.
- It totally is.

21
00:00:59,009 --> 00:01:01,877
- I want you to meet my friends.
- I know all your friends.

22
00:01:01,979 --> 00:01:03,444
You know all my doctor friends.

23
00:01:03,547 --> 00:01:06,347
I'm a patient now. You
gotta meet my patient friends.

24
00:01:06,449 --> 00:01:08,394
And they are gonna
love my new husband.

25
00:01:08,418 --> 00:01:11,119
- Don't make a big deal.
- I'm not gonna make a big deal.

26
00:01:11,221 --> 00:01:14,656
I'm a bride!

27
00:01:14,758 --> 00:01:16,809
Iz, come on. I'm
getting her a real one.

28
00:01:16,894 --> 00:01:19,361
I love this one. That
makes it a real one.

29
00:01:19,463 --> 00:01:23,916
- Everybody, this is Alex. My husband.
- Hi.

30
00:01:24,018 --> 00:01:28,637
Husband, this is Austin,
Star, Meg, Miguel and Alison.

31
00:01:28,739 --> 00:01:31,406
Can you turn him around
so we can see the butt?

32
00:01:31,509 --> 00:01:34,476
- Yes. Alex?
- What, are you kidding me?

33
00:01:36,146 --> 00:01:39,314
Oh! A big trauma
just came in. That's...

34
00:01:40,467 --> 00:01:41,877
- That's quality booty.
- Right?

35
00:01:41,901 --> 00:01:44,252
- Congratulations, Izzie.
- Thank you.

36
00:01:48,342 --> 00:01:52,344
So, uh, I had a good session
with my shrink this morning.

37
00:01:53,413 --> 00:01:55,813
Did you talk to her
about your mom?

38
00:01:58,602 --> 00:02:00,135
Have you seen your mom yet?

39
00:02:00,237 --> 00:02:01,998
'Cause she lives
a few miles away,

40
00:02:02,022 --> 00:02:03,300
and she thinks you're in Iraq.

41
00:02:03,324 --> 00:02:07,459
- I am planning to see her.
- When?

42
00:02:13,450 --> 00:02:15,617
Dr. Hunt? I'm not
on trauma today?

43
00:02:15,719 --> 00:02:17,602
Follow me, O'Malley.

44
00:02:19,306 --> 00:02:21,939
Lieutenant Lowell, I'm
Dr. Hunt, we spoke on the phone.

45
00:02:22,042 --> 00:02:23,670
Major Hunt, it's good
to finally meet you.

46
00:02:23,694 --> 00:02:25,271
My CO's told me a lot about you.

47
00:02:25,295 --> 00:02:27,845
You shouldn't believe
anything Steve Mason tells you.

48
00:02:27,947 --> 00:02:30,115
This is Dr. O'Malley,
you've met Dr. Torres.

49
00:02:30,217 --> 00:02:33,201
I'm looking at Charlie's
scans, but not finding anything

50
00:02:33,303 --> 00:02:34,614
functionally wrong with the leg.

51
00:02:34,638 --> 00:02:37,772
Except I can't walk
or run or move,

52
00:02:37,874 --> 00:02:40,441
really, without serious
pain. I've tried everything.

53
00:02:40,543 --> 00:02:42,978
Medications, physical
therapy, nothing works.

54
00:02:43,080 --> 00:02:45,008
Which could indicate
nerve damage.

55
00:02:45,032 --> 00:02:46,464
Or chronic pain syndrome.

56
00:02:46,567 --> 00:02:49,785
And we can look into pain
management, but surgically,

57
00:02:49,903 --> 00:02:52,154
I'm afraid there's
nothing I can do.

58
00:02:53,523 --> 00:02:55,240
Actually, there is.

59
00:02:56,693 --> 00:02:57,959
You could cut it off.

60
00:02:58,061 --> 00:03:01,062
You can cut it off, replace
it with a prosthetic leg

61
00:03:01,165 --> 00:03:03,632
so I can get back to
Iraq, where I'm needed.

62
00:03:18,398 --> 00:03:20,064
- Did you know why he was here?
- No.

63
00:03:20,166 --> 00:03:21,811
Is it such an
unreasonable request?

64
00:03:21,835 --> 00:03:24,469
Unreasonable? Cutting off a
viable limb is dismemberment.

65
00:03:24,571 --> 00:03:26,891
That kid made lieutenant at 19.

66
00:03:26,924 --> 00:03:29,290
He was planning on
spending his life in the military.

67
00:03:29,392 --> 00:03:31,009
They'll take him
back with one leg?

68
00:03:31,111 --> 00:03:34,746
There have been amputees who've
returned to duty with prosthetics.

69
00:03:34,848 --> 00:03:36,793
- Voluntary amputees?
- Maybe, I don't know.

70
00:03:36,817 --> 00:03:38,377
I have to turn this kid away?

71
00:03:38,401 --> 00:03:41,420
His CO sent him here
because he trusts me.

72
00:03:41,522 --> 00:03:43,105
We could get
another set of scans

73
00:03:43,207 --> 00:03:45,327
and then try an
epidural for the pain.

74
00:03:46,076 --> 00:03:48,793
Dr. Torres?

75
00:03:48,895 --> 00:03:51,780
Fine. Do an MRI and an epidural.
I'll take a look at the scans,

76
00:03:51,882 --> 00:03:54,549
but if the leg is healthy,
I'm not cutting it off.

77
00:03:59,556 --> 00:04:02,290
- Dr. Bailey, you busy today?
- That depends.

78
00:04:02,392 --> 00:04:04,809
You got any dying children
you want me to become

79
00:04:04,911 --> 00:04:06,890
overly attached to
before they expire?

80
00:04:06,914 --> 00:04:09,130
I have an eight-year-old
neuroblastoma patient

81
00:04:09,232 --> 00:04:11,316
and he's gonna live.
I feel it in my bones.

82
00:04:11,418 --> 00:04:13,218
So scrub in with
me and see the joy.

83
00:04:13,320 --> 00:04:16,888
Dr. Bailey, may I borrow you?

84
00:04:18,408 --> 00:04:21,042
- Who is Santa Claus?
- An old, white man

85
00:04:21,144 --> 00:04:22,622
who lives at the North Pole

86
00:04:22,646 --> 00:04:24,779
and enters people's
homes inappropriately?

87
00:04:24,881 --> 00:04:26,348
No.

88
00:04:27,551 --> 00:04:30,017
I'm Santa Claus.

89
00:04:32,005 --> 00:04:34,205
<i>All systems ready.</i>

90
00:04:34,290 --> 00:04:37,358
Oh, no, you did not!

91
00:04:37,460 --> 00:04:42,714
Oh, yes, I did. The Da
Vinci S-I HD Surgical System.

92
00:04:42,816 --> 00:04:45,784
Tell me you didn't
wait until I'd all but left

93
00:04:45,886 --> 00:04:48,753
the general surgery
program to buy the Da Vinci.

94
00:04:48,855 --> 00:04:51,723
Care to take it out for a spin?

95
00:04:51,825 --> 00:04:54,726
Santa!

96
00:04:56,196 --> 00:04:57,707
Hey. I was thinking, you know,

97
00:04:57,731 --> 00:05:00,499
with Derek and
Meredith getting married,

98
00:05:00,601 --> 00:05:02,077
they probably don't
want us hanging out

99
00:05:02,101 --> 00:05:03,501
in the attic much longer.

100
00:05:03,603 --> 00:05:07,372
So I was thinking I'd
start looking for a condo.

101
00:05:07,474 --> 00:05:10,024
Perfect. Then you'd finally
have a place of your own.

102
00:05:10,127 --> 00:05:14,629
Actually, I was, you know,
thinking maybe you'd, uh...

103
00:05:14,731 --> 00:05:16,476
- you'd come with me.
- Absolutely.

104
00:05:16,500 --> 00:05:19,718
I'd love to see it. I
am so happy for you.

105
00:05:25,225 --> 00:05:27,025
How much of that did you hear?

106
00:05:27,127 --> 00:05:28,704
The part where you asked
her to move in with you

107
00:05:28,728 --> 00:05:30,778
or where she shot you down?

108
00:05:30,880 --> 00:05:33,681
I was here for both.
And, by the way,

109
00:05:33,784 --> 00:05:36,484
it's just way too early for
you to be moving in with Lexie.

110
00:05:36,586 --> 00:05:38,537
You don't have to
do everything I do.

111
00:05:38,639 --> 00:05:39,921
This is not about you.

112
00:05:40,023 --> 00:05:42,657
I have my own future to
think about. Life is short.

113
00:05:42,759 --> 00:05:44,826
Look at what's going
on with Stevens.

114
00:05:44,944 --> 00:05:47,278
Don't worry about
Stevens. I got a plan.

115
00:05:47,380 --> 00:05:49,392
You want to remove
her hippocampus?

116
00:05:49,416 --> 00:05:51,599
One of them. It's a
common procedure.

117
00:05:51,701 --> 00:05:53,585
Removing her hippocampus
could compromise

118
00:05:53,687 --> 00:05:54,886
her memory, her speech.

119
00:05:54,988 --> 00:05:57,350
She wouldn't be able
to practice medicine.

120
00:05:57,374 --> 00:05:59,969
- I've performed this
hundreds of times.
- On cancer patients?

121
00:05:59,993 --> 00:06:01,893
- No, but it's...
- If you do it,

122
00:06:01,995 --> 00:06:03,275
I could lose my memory?

123
00:06:05,599 --> 00:06:07,432
It's unlikely,
but it's possible.

124
00:06:07,534 --> 00:06:09,162
And if you don't
do the surgery...

125
00:06:09,186 --> 00:06:11,147
We could shrink
the tumor with IL2.

126
00:06:11,171 --> 00:06:13,599
- If the tumor doesn't kill me first.
- - Why take the chance?

127
00:06:13,623 --> 00:06:16,863
- Have you done a Wada test?
- - Putting her brain to sleep and asking her

128
00:06:16,910 --> 00:06:19,511
to remember flash
cards is not an accurate...

129
00:06:19,613 --> 00:06:22,280
But it would tell us whether
or not she could function after.

130
00:06:22,382 --> 00:06:24,994
- As her physician...
- Fine, I'll do it. It's unnecessary.

131
00:06:25,018 --> 00:06:26,563
The surgery is unnecessary.

132
00:06:26,587 --> 00:06:28,319
She's having hallucinations.

133
00:06:42,069 --> 00:06:44,069
Nice ring.

134
00:06:44,170 --> 00:06:45,953
Alex outdid himself.

135
00:06:46,056 --> 00:06:49,707
We're gonna have beautiful
kids, don't you think?

136
00:06:49,810 --> 00:06:53,828
- Is four too many?
- Four is perfect.

137
00:06:53,930 --> 00:06:56,331
Ideally, it would be
two boys and two girls.

138
00:06:56,433 --> 00:06:59,584
One of which will
definitely be a tomboy.

139
00:06:59,686 --> 00:07:01,452
And I should have
them close together,

140
00:07:01,554 --> 00:07:03,421
though that might be stupid.

141
00:07:03,523 --> 00:07:06,024
- Why wait?
- Exactly.

142
00:07:06,126 --> 00:07:09,961
That way, if I'm not able to
practice medicine anymore...

143
00:07:10,063 --> 00:07:13,031
- You won't want to.
- You don't think?

144
00:07:13,133 --> 00:07:15,767
- Do you?
- I'm asking you.

145
00:07:15,869 --> 00:07:19,086
Why do you keep agreeing
with everything I say?

146
00:07:19,188 --> 00:07:22,189
Because I am
you. I'm your tumor.

147
00:07:22,291 --> 00:07:25,560
You're talking to yourself.

148
00:07:25,662 --> 00:07:28,930
- Right.
- At least until
you have surgery.

149
00:07:29,032 --> 00:07:34,252
If you have surgery. Are
you gonna have surgery?

150
00:07:50,436 --> 00:07:54,773
If Derek cuts the tumor
out, I could lose my memory.

151
00:07:54,875 --> 00:07:58,609
And if he doesn't, I could
die. I don't know what to do.

152
00:07:58,712 --> 00:08:01,863
- Alex, tell me what to do.
- I can't tell you what to do.

153
00:08:01,965 --> 00:08:03,893
Of course. You're my husband.

154
00:08:03,917 --> 00:08:05,862
That's what husbands
do. They stomp around

155
00:08:05,886 --> 00:08:08,553
telling their wives
what to do. It's your job.

156
00:08:08,655 --> 00:08:12,507
- My job is to support you.
- I don't know
what I want to do.

157
00:08:12,609 --> 00:08:14,342
That's why I'm asking you.

158
00:08:15,995 --> 00:08:19,480
OK, I have an idea.
Let's put it to a vote.

159
00:08:19,582 --> 00:08:22,250
- All in favor of the surgery.
- We're not voting.

160
00:08:22,352 --> 00:08:23,613
No one's voting.

161
00:08:23,637 --> 00:08:27,505
- Opposed?
- I'm opposed.

162
00:08:27,607 --> 00:08:31,626
- To voting.
- Just decide for me. Please?

163
00:08:31,728 --> 00:08:34,829
You don't have to know
right now. Think about it.

164
00:08:34,931 --> 00:08:37,148
I don't have time.

165
00:08:42,438 --> 00:08:44,071
Captain Mason told
me you saved his life

166
00:08:44,174 --> 00:08:45,439
four times in the field.

167
00:08:45,541 --> 00:08:48,576
A couple in the canteen, but
don't tell Mace I told you that.

168
00:08:48,678 --> 00:08:51,228
So you think I'll
get to go back?

169
00:08:53,249 --> 00:08:54,682
Are you sure you want to?

170
00:08:54,784 --> 00:08:58,319
I mean, why do you
want to cut off your leg

171
00:08:58,421 --> 00:09:02,056
just to go back to the
war? Don't you have family?

172
00:09:02,158 --> 00:09:04,909
You know what it's like to
have family who don't know you,

173
00:09:05,011 --> 00:09:08,663
don't get you, maybe
don't even like you?

174
00:09:08,765 --> 00:09:11,465
Yeah, actually, I have brothers.

175
00:09:11,567 --> 00:09:13,951
Me too.

176
00:09:14,053 --> 00:09:16,573
So there's that family,
the guys I grew up with,

177
00:09:16,656 --> 00:09:17,955
and we've got nothing in common.

178
00:09:18,057 --> 00:09:20,825
And then there's
my guys in Iraq.

179
00:09:23,013 --> 00:09:26,014
My real family.

180
00:09:26,116 --> 00:09:29,484
Whatever we got into,
we were in it together.

181
00:09:29,586 --> 00:09:32,670
But here, I'm alone. I'm nobody.

182
00:09:32,772 --> 00:09:36,074
And I've tried. I've
tried fitting in here.

183
00:09:36,176 --> 00:09:37,742
I've tried being
a regular person.

184
00:09:37,844 --> 00:09:41,413
I've tried getting a job,
but there aren't any.

185
00:09:41,514 --> 00:09:43,759
There are a lot of things
I wanted to be in my life,

186
00:09:43,783 --> 00:09:45,650
things I wanted to do.

187
00:09:46,303 --> 00:09:48,436
But none of 'em's here.

188
00:09:53,493 --> 00:09:54,408
This is Alison Clark.

189
00:09:54,510 --> 00:09:56,628
She was referred
to me two years ago.

190
00:09:56,730 --> 00:09:58,808
Mets in her
brain, liver, kidney.

191
00:09:58,832 --> 00:10:01,216
She ended up
having five surgeries

192
00:10:01,318 --> 00:10:03,551
and extensive
chemo, which worked.

193
00:10:03,653 --> 00:10:04,869
But then...

194
00:10:08,291 --> 00:10:13,861
- The mets came back.
- That's when I started
her IL2 therapy.

195
00:10:13,963 --> 00:10:17,932
And now, after three
treatments in as many months...

196
00:10:21,821 --> 00:10:25,223
- The mets are gone?
- The mets are gone.

197
00:10:25,325 --> 00:10:28,259
Dr. Stevens should be patient.

198
00:10:28,362 --> 00:10:30,895
She should give her
therapies a chance.

199
00:10:30,998 --> 00:10:36,534
As surgeons, we like to cut. But
sometimes there's a better way.

200
00:10:42,041 --> 00:10:44,003
Let me retract that small bowel

201
00:10:44,027 --> 00:10:45,860
so you'll have
better visualization.

202
00:10:45,962 --> 00:10:48,596
You know what,
chief? Thanks to Leo,

203
00:10:48,698 --> 00:10:49,997
you don't have to.

204
00:10:50,100 --> 00:10:54,335
- Leo?
- Leonardo. Da Vinci.

205
00:10:54,437 --> 00:10:57,538
Watch this. See?

206
00:10:57,640 --> 00:11:01,775
Five hundred and forty
degrees of wristed movement.

207
00:11:03,380 --> 00:11:05,013
Can't do that with
a laparoscope.

208
00:11:05,115 --> 00:11:06,625
Or in open surgery.

209
00:11:06,649 --> 00:11:08,766
Feels pretty good, doesn't it?

210
00:11:14,875 --> 00:11:18,609
Dr. Bailey? Are you
making lightsaber noises?

211
00:11:18,712 --> 00:11:21,979
Uh, not anymore, sir.

212
00:11:23,517 --> 00:11:26,684
You know, Dr. Chalikonda
at Cleveland Clinic is doing

213
00:11:26,786 --> 00:11:29,287
single-incision
gallbladder removal

214
00:11:29,389 --> 00:11:32,724
through the belly button. We
can try that on the next one.

215
00:11:35,261 --> 00:11:38,462
- If you're up to it.
- Don't tease me, sir.

216
00:11:38,565 --> 00:11:42,750
I'm not. Why should
Dr. Chalikonda have all the fun?

217
00:11:51,911 --> 00:11:55,429
It's impressive, but it took
two years to get these results.

218
00:11:55,532 --> 00:11:57,031
These were three months apart.

219
00:11:57,133 --> 00:11:59,078
Izzie may not have three months.

220
00:11:59,102 --> 00:12:02,854
That tumor could start bleeding
in three days. Or three seconds.

221
00:12:02,956 --> 00:12:05,101
Since when are you
not about cutting?

222
00:12:05,125 --> 00:12:06,908
It may not be in
the best interest.

223
00:12:07,010 --> 00:12:09,844
Derek's not acting in
Izzie's best interests?

224
00:12:13,266 --> 00:12:15,547
They're ready
for us in radiology.

225
00:12:31,367 --> 00:12:33,768
OK, Iz, I'm going to show you...

226
00:12:33,870 --> 00:12:35,620
a series of images you want me

227
00:12:35,722 --> 00:12:37,989
to try to remember once
Derek puts the right side

228
00:12:38,074 --> 00:12:39,424
of my brain to sleep.

229
00:12:39,526 --> 00:12:40,526
Mm-hm.

230
00:12:40,576 --> 00:12:43,378
- Hit me. Show me what you got.
- OK.

231
00:12:43,480 --> 00:12:45,563
Is that a schnauzer
or a Scottie?

232
00:12:45,665 --> 00:12:47,226
How specific do I need to be?

233
00:12:47,250 --> 00:12:48,716
Dog is fine.

234
00:12:49,752 --> 00:12:54,172
- It's either a 727 or a 747.
- Plane.

235
00:12:56,159 --> 00:12:58,559
Ooh. A two-story
Victorian mansion.

236
00:12:58,661 --> 00:13:00,678
We would also
accept the word house.

237
00:13:00,780 --> 00:13:04,798
Schnauzer, 747, mansion,
schnauzer, 747, mansion.

238
00:13:04,900 --> 00:13:07,635
Or dog, plane, house.

239
00:13:07,737 --> 00:13:10,705
I'm putting the right hemisphere
of your brain to sleep now, OK?

240
00:13:10,807 --> 00:13:14,025
Dog, plane, house,
